      "Codes vs ciphers and classic cipher types: Codes = systems of symbols that sometimes imply secrecy but do not always provide confidentiality (e.g. Morse code); Ciphers = always designed to provide secrecy via key-based transformation; Substitution cipher = replaces each character with a different character (Caesar cipher = fixed shift; Vigenere = word/phrase key; One-time pad = key same length as message); Transposition cipher = rearranges the letters of plaintext without substituting characters (e.g. rail fence); Caesar = key length 1, Vigenere = multi-character key, OTP = same length as message — longer keys = stronger",
